     <h2><font color="#000080"><!-- 2004-09-02 -->
	 
	 The Passing of Salvatore Lombino: Farewell, 87th Precinct
	 </font>
     </h2>
    

	<p>
    <div style="clear:both;"></div><p><a href="http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2002367940_hunterobit08.html?syndication=rss">The Seattle Times: Nation &amp; World: Evan Hunter dies; he was better known as Ed McBain</a>.&nbsp; It was sad to read of the death of writer Evan Hunter, 78.&nbsp; I&rsquo;m grateful for Cara Rubinsky&rsquo;s Associated Press report with its homage to one of my favorites.</p><p>I have been a fan of Hunter and his alter ego, Ed McBain, for a long time and I was always bemused that he was also the author of <em>The Blackboard Jungle</em>, though I didn&rsquo;t know that when I began reading about the 87th Precinct in the&nbsp;&rsquo;60s.&nbsp; </p><p>I don&rsquo;t know&nbsp;the accuracy&nbsp;in&nbsp;his treatment of police work, but his ongoing ensemble treatment brought us into the lives of his characters.&nbsp;&nbsp;I introduced Vicki to the 87th Precinct while she was reading everything in sight during a recuperation last year.&nbsp; We began to discuss the stories at the dinner table.&nbsp; The one&nbsp;quality that stands out&nbsp;for us is how easily we are able to&nbsp;care what happens to the characters in the stories, even the villains and the&nbsp;less-than-appealing denizens of the precinct house.&nbsp; We are left wondering how Detective Stephen Louis&nbsp;Carella will resolve his despair over&nbsp;his newly arrived step-father and brother-in-law as nothing remains the same, except Teddy, constant Teddy.&nbsp; Do you think Fat Ollie ever learns to play &ldquo;Spanish Eyes?&rdquo;&nbsp;</p><p>I&rsquo;m grateful for the last-read offerings from Evan Hunter&rsquo;s pen: <em>The Frumious Bandersnatch</em> and <em>Hark</em> (of the 87th precinct as Ed McBain), <em>Alice in Jeopardy</em> (a different Ed McBain), and <em>Candyland</em> (a novel in two parts,&nbsp;started by&nbsp;Evan Hunter and&nbsp;finished by&nbsp;Ed McBain).&nbsp; Most of all, I am grateful for&nbsp;the gift and lesson of humanity invested in&nbsp;all of those&nbsp;characters who so wonderfully memorialize their author.</p><p align="center"><strong><font color="#c00080"><small>{updated for tagging: </font></strong><a href="http://honortags.com/HonorTagPersonal" rel="tag"><strong><font color="#c00080">HonorTagPersonal</font></strong></a><strong><font color="#c00080"> </font></strong><a href="http://technorati.com/tag/Ed_McBain" rel="tag"><strong><font color="#c00080">Ed McBain</font></strong></a><strong><font color="#c00080"> </font></strong><a href="http://technorati.com/tag/87th_Precinct" rel="tag"><strong><font color="#c00080">87th Precinct</font></strong></a><strong><font color="#c00080"> </font></strong><a href="http://technorati.com/tag/Evan_Hunter" rel="tag"><strong><font color="#c00080">Evan Hunter</font></strong></a><strong><font color="#c00080"> </font></strong><a href="http://technorati.com/tag/mysteries" rel="tag"><strong><font color="#c00080">mysteries</font></strong></a><strong><font color="#c00080">}</small></font></strong></p><div style="clear:both; padding-bottom: 0.25em;"></div>
    </p>
